A targeted fall night electrofishing survey was conducted on Norway during September 30, 2018 to evaluate young of year "YOY" (fingerling sized) Walleye numbers due to a fry stocking. Norway is a large (2,339 acres), multi-basin, moderate depth (33 feet maximum) and productive lake located in Kandiyohi County.

Walleye natural reproduction contribution in Norway is variable based on previous surveys and standard analysis. Walleye fry (1.6-3.8 million) had been stocked in Norway from 2007-2010 (various strains) and 2012 (Spicer strain). Oxytetracycline "OTC" marked fry were stocked in 2009 (2,152,425 Private and Spicer strain fish) and 2016 (885,643 Spicer strain fish). Unmarked Spicer strain Walleye fry (1,132,151) were stocked in 2018. Walleye frylings were stocked in 2011 (16,779 OTC marked Pike/Red River strain fish) and 2014 (33,373 OTC marked Pike River strain fish). A combination of Walleye fingerlings, adults and yearlings were stocked in 2008 (85,235 fingerlings, 1,864 pounds), 2009 (11,651 yearlings, 987 pounds; 318 fingerlings, 91 pounds; 360 adults, 287 pounds), 2011 (15,477 fingerlings, 737 pounds; 1,400 yearlings, 200 pounds; 3 adults, 6 pounds) and 2012 (16,842 yearlings, 802 pounds).

Moderate YOY Walleye numbers (56.40 YOY/hour, 6.08 inches) were captured in the 2018 fall electrofishing survey. A fall electrofishing survey was not conducted on Norway in 2017. Abundant YOY Walleye numbers (94.00 YOY/hour, 6.36 inches) were captured in the 2016 fall night electrofishing survey. OTC marked fish accounted for 67% of the 2016 Fall YOY Walleye Catch. Low YOY walleye numbers (16.00 YOY/hour, 6.73 inches) due to natural reproduction were captured in the 2015 fall electrofishing survey. Moderate YOY Walleye numbers (50.00 YOY/hour, 6.10 inches) were captured in the 2014 fall electrofishing survey. OTC marked fish accounted for 42% (21.00 YOY/hour) of the 2014 fall electrofishing YOY Walleye catch rate. Low numbers of YOY Walleye (4.00 YOY/hour, 6.89 inches) due to natural reproduction were captured during the 2013 fall electrofishing survey. YOY Walleye numbers were moderate to low due to fry stocking and/or natural reproduction (32.00 YOY/hour, 6.04 inches) in the 2012 fall electrofishing survey. YOY Walleye abundance was low due to natural reproduction in the 2011 fall electrofishing survey (14.00 YOY/hour, 6.73 inches), but high due to fry stocking and/or natural reproduction (72.00 YOY/hour, 6.12 inches) in the 2010 fall electrofishing survey. Low numbers of Walleye frylings (OTC marked) were stocked into Norway during the 2011 summer (16,779 fish); however no marked fish were captured in the 2011 fall electrofishing survey. We observed abundant to moderate numbers of YOY Freshwater Drum, Bluegill, Yellow Perch, Black Crappie, Shiners and Largemouth Bass in the 2018 fall electrofishing survey.

No yearling Walleye were captured in 2018 or 2016. Low yearling Walleye numbers (4.00 fish/hour, 8.92 inches) were captured in 2015. There were moderate numbers of yearling Walleye (14.00 fish/hour, 8.23 inches) captured in 2014. No yearling Walleye were captured in 2013 fall survey. Yearling Walleye numbers were abundant (22.00 fish/hour, 8.83 inches) in the 2012 fall electrofishing survey. Yearling Walleye catch rates were 18.00 YOY/hour (9.60 inches) in 2011 and 21.00 YOY/hour (9.90 inches) in 2010.

Adult Walleye abundance (8.40 fish/gillnet) was within the normal ranges for Norway and similar lakes in the most recent 2015 summer gillnet survey. The 2015 Walleye average weight and length were 1.36 pounds and 15.15 inches from gillnets. The 2012 and 2014 Walleye year classes comprised 44% and 17% respectively of the 2015 Walleye summer gillnet and trapnet catch.

The Norway Lake fishery will be surveyed in the 2019 summer for all fish species. Fall electrofishing surveys will be conducted during Walleye fry or fryling stocked years to assess the success or failure of the stockings.

A standard survey was conducted on Norway Lake during late July of 2019. A targeted survey is generally used for sampling a specific kind of fish or time of year (i.e. spawning season, fall season, etc.) unlike a standard survey which samples a wider range of fish species during the summer months using standard methodology (i.e. standard time of year, set sampling stations, taking water clarity readings and oxygen/temperature profiles, etc.) and gears (i.e. lake survey gillnets, trapnets and possibly spring electrofishing for Largemouth Bass). Two Index of Biotic Integrity "FIBI" targeted surveys for all near shore fish species were conducted in August of 2019. A Fall Electrofishing targeted survey for young of year "YOY" Walleye in September of 2019.

Norway is a large sized (2,339 acres), moderately deep (33 feet maximum depth), multi basin (West Norway, Big Norway, Little Norway), and productive lake located in Kandiyohi County. West Norway basin (approximately 1,300 acres) is a shallow (<10 feet deep), turbid, and windswept basin with high nutrient levels and limited submergent vegetation. Little Norway basin (150 acres) is a protected and shallow (<10 feet deep) basin with abundant aquatic vegetation. The Big Norway basin (approximately 900 acres) is 33 feet deep maximum with moderate aquatic vegetation densities and moderate water clarity. There are 328 lake homes/cabins, 53 recreational vehicles and 2 resorts that existed along the lakeshore in 2010. Norway receives moderate recreational and angling use in the summer from local residents, visitors to the resorts, and lakeshore homeowners. The immediate watershed is mostly agricultural row crops with lesser amounts of residential development, wetlands and hardwood stands. There are 8 inlets that flow into the various Norway basins and an outlet channel that flows into Games Lake. Two large inlets carry significant agricultural runoff which includes Kandiyohi County Ditches 27 & 29. Nutrient levels are generally high to moderate in the lake. Water levels were high during 2019. Dissolved oxygen levels were above 5.0 ppm to depths of 18 feet. Water clarity was fair to poor during July of 2019 (secchi reading=3.0 feet). Blue-green algae blooms are common and intense during late summer especially in the West Norway basin. The Engen Northern Pike Spawning Area (1979 acquired) is located on the southwest shore of the West Norway basin. There are two Norway Aquatic Management Area "AMA" tracts (Larson and Little Norway). The Larson Tract (2011 acquired) is located along a channel between the main and West Norway basins. A recently acquired Norway "AMA" Little Norway Tract (2014) is located on the southwest side of Little Norway and north side of the main basin. Little Norway basin connects to Games Lake via a narrow outlet channel. Water flows out of Games Lake and eventually downstream into Swan, Henchien, Andrew and Florida. Aquatic vegetation was surveyed at 40 transect sites in 2010 and 2019. Emergent vegetation consisted of scattered stands of cattails and hardstem bulrush in all three basins. Submergent vegetation density was light to moderate in 2019 consisting mostly of sago pondweed, bushy pondweed, water celery, muskgrass, northern milfoil, Eurasian watermilfoil "EWM", coontail, clasping-leaf pondweed flat-stemmed pondweed and water moss within the shallow areas (< 10 feet deep). Eurasian watermilfoil was found scattered throughout the West Norway basin in August of 2001 and in the Big Norway basin during 2005. Eurasian watermilfoil was found at 30% of the transect sites in 2010, but 75% of the transect sites in 2019. Although Eurasian watermilfoil is present at most sites, densities are generally low to moderate in all three Norway basins. Eurasian watermilfoil is also present in downstream lakes of Games (2014), Andrew (2019) and Florida (2009). Zebra Mussels were found in Norway, Games and Andrew in 2018. Shoalwater substrates consist mostly of sand, silt, gravel, rubble, and boulder in Norway.

Norway lies within the larger Chippewa River Watershed District and sub watershed of Upper Shakopee Creek. The Chippewa River Watershed District was the lead agency for coordinating: nutrient reduction measures, protection from invasive species, information/education, storm water management and the Shakopee Creek Headwaters Project prior to 2019. The local Soil Water Conservation District is currently the lead agency.

The two large Kandiyohi County Ditches (CD 27 & 29) upstream of Norway are considered the headwaters of Shakopee Creek. An intensive watershed study of water flow and nutrient runoff was conducted on Andrew, Games, and Norway Lakes in addition to associated inlets from 1996-1998. A group of private landowners and public conservation agency personnel have been involved in the Shakopee Creek Headwaters Project. The Shakopee Creek Headwaters group has monitored water quality and flows in the watershed, encouraged landowners to implement best management practices through grant funding, utilized existing government programs, provided education, and technical assistance. Thus far, DNR Fisheries has provided assistance with lakeshore re-vegetation and water quality monitoring projects within the watershed.

A targeted survey of nearshore fish species was attempted by seine hauls and backpack electrofishing at 24 Fish-based Index of Biologic Integrity "FIBI" stations. We sampled 22 stations by near shore electrofishing and 19 stations by seining. Two stations (EFB16 & EFB17) were not accessible for electrofishing or seining in a shallow south bay. Approximately 26 different fish species (17 species from back-pack electrofishing, and 22 species from seining) were captured from electrofishing and seining combined. Fish species captured included gamefish (i.e. Northern Pike and Largemouth Bass), panfish (Bluegill, Black Crappie, Yellow Perch, Pumpkinseed, Green Sunfish, and Hybrid Sunfish), potentially large sized non-gamefish (Common Carp, Bigmouth Buffalo, Freshwater Drum, Yellow Bullhead, Black Bullhead and White Sucker) and small sized non-gamefish (Iowa Darter, Johnny Darter, Banded Killifish, Fathead Minnow, Bluntnose Minnow, Central Mudminnow, Tadpole Madtom, Golden Shiner, Pugnose Shiner, Spottail Shiner and Blackchin Shiner).

Fish that require narrow habitat (e.g. continual water flow, submerged woody material, gravel substrate, abundant bulrush vegetation, undisturbed near shore areas, etc.) or water quality conditions (e.g. high clarity, low iron concentrations, moderate phosphorus availability, specific temperature/oxygen ranges, etc.) are classified as intolerant habitat disturbance species. Examples of intolerant habitat disturbance species captured in the FIBI survey included: Iowa Darter, Pugnose Shiner, Blackchin Shiner and Banded Killifish captured in Norway. High tolerant habitat disturbance species captured included: Black Bullhead, Bigmouth Buffalo, Common Carp, Green Sunfish and Fathead Minnow. The FIBI uses fish community data to measure a lake's health, and the types of fish species present can help identify any stressors that may be negatively affecting the lake environment. The FIBI score was good (51) for Norway, which is above the impairment threshold (36) for this set of similar statewide lakes.

The following results are based on standard summer survey gillnetting and trapnetting, spring Largemouth Bass Electrofishing and YOY Walleye fall electrofishing catches:

Northern Pike numbers were low in 2019 (2.00 fish/gillnet). The Northern Pike historical average catch rate is 4.86 fish/gillnet. The 2019 Northern Pike average size was moderate (3.86 pounds and 25.65 inches) from gillnets. The Northern Pike historical average weight is 3.36 pounds from gillnets. Northern Pike growth rates were fair. The 2013 and 2012 year classes comprised 29% and 25% respectively in the 2019 Northern Pike survey catch. Norway has a history of producing large Northern Pike. The largest Northern Pike captured was 33.03 inches in the 2019 survey nets. Northern Pike possession limit regulations for Norway in the North-central Zone are as follows: anglers can keep 10 Northern Pike, but not more than two pike longer than 26 inches; and all from 22 to 26 inches must be released. Northern Pike taken by spearing follow the same rules except one pike may be between 22 and 26 inches or two larger than 26 inches.

There is adequate Northern Pike spawning habitat within Norway and adjacent upstream wetland areas, however natural reproduction or recruitment has been poor in recent years. It is unclear if chemical runoff pollution, low spring water levels, degraded habitat or a combination of factors is negatively affecting Northern Pike recruitment in Norway. The Engen Northern Pike Spawning Area "NPSA" had been used to produce modest Northern Pike fingerling numbers in past years. In prior years, the spawning structure was in need of repair. The Engen NPSA water control structure and dike was repaired with cooperation from the West Central Chapter of the Minnesota Darkhouse & Angling Association in 2012. However, low water levels prevented the use of Engen NPSA in 2014 and 2015. Northern Pike were recently stocked from a variety of sources in 2013 (383 fingerlings, 98 adults; Engen NPSA), 2014 (702 adults; winter rescue sources), 2015 (9,532 fingerlings; New London Hatchery Pond Production) 2016 (4,766 fingerlings, 79 adults; Engen NPSA), 2017 (500 fingerlings; Engen NPSA) and 2018 (24,324 fry, 330 fingerlings; Engen NPSA).

Bluegill numbers were high in 2019 (41.94 fish/trapnet). The Bluegill historical average catch rate is 22.36 fish/trapnet. The 2019 Bluegill average size was small (0.08 pounds and 4.73 inches) from trapnets. The Bluegill historical average weight is 0.16 pounds from trapnets. There were no Bluegill over 8.00 inches captured in the 2019 survey nets.

Black Crappie numbers were low in 2019 (6.59 fish/trapnet) compared to the historical average catch rate of 9.51 fish/trapnet. The 2019 Black Crappie average size was small (0.18 pounds and 6.18 inches) from trapnets. The Black Crappie historical average weight is 0.27 pounds from trapnets. Black Crappie growth rates were slow to moderate. The 2018 and 2015 year classes comprised 74% and 9% respectively of the 2019 Black Crappie survey catch.

Largemouth Bass numbers were abundant (41.00 fish/hour) in the 2019 post spawn mid-June electrofishing survey. Sampling was done at 6 representative sampling stations. The 2019 Largemouth Bass average size was moderate (1.02 pounds and 11.30 inches). A previous electrofishing survey for Largemouth Bass was conducted during post spawn conditions at three historical (bulrush) sites in mid-June of 2015 (30.40 fish/hour, 11.71 inches average length). Largemouth Bass growth rates were fair. The 2015 and 2016 year classes each comprised 22% of the 2019 Largemouth Bass catch from mid-June electrofishing.

Yellow Perch numbers were abundant in 2019 (36.00 fish/gillnet) compared to the historical average catch rate of 18.67 fish/gillnet. The 2019 Yellow Perch average size was small (0.11 pounds and 6.27 inches) from gillnets.

Walleye numbers were abundant in 2019 (12.67 fish/gillnet). The Walleye historical average catch rate is 7.33 fish/gillnet. The 2019 Walleye average size was moderate (1.26 pounds and 14.98 inches) from gillnets. The 2019 catch rate of quality size (15.00 inches and larger) Walleye was also high (6.83 fish/gillnet) for Norway. Walleye growth rates were fair. The 2016 and 2015 Walleye year classes comprised 35% and 17% respectively of the 2019 Walleye gillnet and trapnet catch. Young of Year "YOY" Walleye numbers in fall electrofishing surveys were abundant in 2016 (94.00 YOY/hour); moderate in 2012 (32.00 YOY/hour), 2014 (50.00 YOY/hour) and 2018 (56.40 YOY/hour); low in 2011 (14.00 YOY/hour), 2013 (4.00 YOY/hour) and 2015 (16.00 YOY/hour). No fall electrofishing survey was conducted in 2017.

Spicer Strain Walleye fry were recently stocked in Norway during 2012 (1,568,599 fry), 2016 (885,643 Oxytetracycline "OTC" marked fry) and 2018 (1,132,151 unmarked fry). OTC marked Walleye frylings were stocked in 2011 (16,779 frylings) and 2014 (33,373 frylings). OTC marked fish accounted for 0%, 42% and 67% respectively of the 2011, 2014 and 2016 fall electrofishing YOY Walleye catch rates. A combination of Walleye fingerlings, adults and yearlings have been stocked in 2008 (85,235 fingerlings, 1,864 pounds), 2009 (11,651 yearlings, 987 pounds; 318 fingerlings, 91 pounds; 360 adults, 287 pounds), 2011 (15,477 fingerlings, 737 pounds; 1,400 yearlings, 200 pounds; 3 adults, 6 pounds) and 2012 (16,842 yearlings, 802 pounds).

Black Bullhead numbers were low in 2019 (0.12 fish/trapnet and 0.50 fish/gillnet). The Black Bullhead historical average catch rates are 1.53 fish/trapnet and 3.32 fish/gillnet for Norway. The 2019 Black Bullhead average size was large (1.04 pounds and 12.15 inches) from trapnets. The Black Bullhead historical average weight is 0.68 pounds from trapnets.

Freshwater Drum numbers were abundant in 2019 (29.17 fish/gillnet). The Freshwater Drum historical average catch rate is 21.61 fish/gillnet for Norway. The 2019 Freshwater Drum average size was moderate (1.18 pounds and 13.90 inches) from gillnets. The Freshwater Drum historical average weight is 1.08 pounds from gillnets.

Common Carp numbers were moderate in 2019 (1.18 fish/trapnet). The Common Carp historical average catch rate is 1.58 fish/trapnet. The 2019 Common Carp average size was moderate (6.40 pounds and 21.95 inches) from trapnets. The historical average weight is 9.49 pounds from trapnets.

Current fish management activities on Norway include monitoring the fish population on a periodic basis, monitoring and preventing the spread of Eurasian watermilfoil in connected waters, assisting aquatic plant management and enforcement personnel in educating boaters and monitoring access sites for other potential invasive species introductions, protecting aquatic vegetation through the permit process, participating in the Shakopee Creek Watershed Project, operating the Engen Northern Pike Spawning Area, and stocking various fish species as warranted. The Norway fishery will be sampled in the 2024 summer for all fish species and 2020 for YOY Walleye.
